After some thought and sleep over the debate from yesterday I can see where Const/Eugene are coming from wanting to implement this change. I was fully on the side of not thinking that implementing the current emissions would be wrong in the beginning, but begin to think that it makes sense for subnets long-term wise to some sense.

I am not still not decided and gathering thoughts on what is the "better solution" and so far every decision has trade-offs, be it changing the EMA, starting equal or starting with the current emissions.

First off why do I think that adding current emissions **could be** bad? The reason we have thought about dTAO and decided the change is needed was because of the subjectivity in root validators setting weights and because only a small set of individuals could decide on the emissions for all subnets. With this in mind, taking over the current emissions would not change the fact where the subnets are and probably hold them near those values over a longer time. They would gain an advantage against root sell pressure from passive price increase coming from the chain, as it want's to "recover" the EMA (because when the price is below the EMA then more TAO_in gets injected than should be to keep the price stable, and thus the price increases by the chain, this was as well a new change by removing TAO downscaling). This could have a rippling effect of how the emission distribution will go forward into the future. People could be incentivized to stake more again into those subnets that start with higher EMAs and thus repeat the same system we have now.

Then, why do I think that not adding current emissions **could be** bad? We have built the economics the existing subnets based on the emissions assigned from root. Subnets and the companies behind those "rely" could rely on the emissions they are getting to pay for infrastructure, employees or possibly many other costs I don't know about as a non-SN owner. Just resetting the market completely and starting all subnets equally could end badly for those that require them the most, while those that are far behind the emissions would get more than "deserved". It would result in chaos for the miners themselves for similar reasons and add more chaos then already gets created through the dTAO upgrade itself.

One of the complaints I have seen by @badenglishtea was and I quote "I don't want to wait 6 months for the subnets who deserve emissions to start receiving them.", but why would we say that those top subnets right now don't deserve them, why would they need to wait for months until possibly being able to go back to the point they were to function normally?

If I would have to think of a "solution"/proposal for those issues mentioned then I would agree on those:
- Start the EMAs at their current emissions, to allow for a smooth transition from the current root weights to the market-driven emissions and not cause the current subnets and their participants to fail
- Possibly and optionally reduce the EMA to have price reflection happening quicker and subnets not having to 1. wait months until their emissions get represented and 2. subnets that drop in emissions because they don't deserve current emission continue to earn emissions from the higher EMA
- Reimplement TAO downscaling to not manipulate the prices, and let the market decide where subnet prices should be, don't add support to EMAs by helping a price to recover towards it. This and the start of current emissions would make it extremely hard to deviate from it once it gets initialized

To finalize off I am kind of disappointed by the senate to not take their time and look into the PR/changes made, that's why those were openly shared and given a timeframe of 6 days to decide, not to all "spam" vote during the hours of the release without actually taking your time at the code. I would have expected more due diligence from those validator teams knowing that they decide for everyone in the community.

Btw I’ve read the code before vote and current implementation will work well enough for the launch. There are several nuances that could be improved, such as decrease of EMA init sum to allow new subnets to compete with existing 64 on emissions faster (days vs months) and auto-dissolution of bad performing / dead subnets, all of that can be updated post-launch if we iterate quickly.

I clearly have a bias in all of this, so will try not to speak about Macrocosmos subnets in this, but a few thoughts. 

-we already have many within Bittensor subnets in operation serving products - if I use SN19 as the example, or many other subnets, forcibly starting them at 1/64 may break production applications. If Glider, Corcel, Targon, Chutes, our soon-to-be-launched Constellation, ReadyAI and everything else just "stops" on Day 1, it's not a great look for the ecosystem if the economic dynamics take a few months to stabilise. We just don't know how this thing will work in anger in Day 1, and the reality is people CANNOT buy in due to slippage / root weight for the first two months without spanking their TAO out.

- the 65th subnet (that doesn't launch in "fair" mode) gets fucked here - also, to be blunt, the 64th subnet that gets in "before the line" receives the same as SN19, and this to me is somewhat nonsensical. I don't see why subnets that have been in the network for over a year and have worked hard to receive community support should be weighted the same as something that secured a slot last week, and that same subnet should be weighted differently to something that secures a slot on dTAO day+1. Again, we can all agree / disagree on this, but to me the comparison between 19, and yet-unnamed slot 28 that just registered is... not exactly logical. 

- I do think the EMA should be very fast -  maybe considering some alignment to the redistribution of alpha to root weight / alpha weight, when subnets are actually investable - this would be stabilising the initial period.

- if everything starts at equal, we are just in a state where MEV whales will be exploiting until the market stabilises - I would argue we're better to allocate in line with the historic root weights (that we have had for 18 months), than allocate in line with whoever has the best slippage script personally.
It seems like one decision will be more profitable for you personally than the other

- I have largely thought about the success of dTAO being pinned to three core forces, and the balance between them - one is just "MEV slippage mechanics" [e.g. gaming the protocol], the second is subnet unit economics [e.g. does it cost a lot to run the subnet compared to a more effective subnet], and the third is the impact of long term investment / buy pressure (e.g. VC / revenue dynamics). If we launch at fair use, we are massively emphasising the first two forces, as the third cannot come online before 60 days - my feeling is we should be doing what we can to balance these forces and allow teams time to adopt. Launching with root start gives time for teams to correct to the 2nd forces, and mitigates the impact of the first... this to me is positive. 

- while there is grift in root, the emissions are I would argue orthogonally correct - less effective subnets are nearer the bottom, better subnets are nearer the top - I don't want to argue about specifics (because there are many incorrect weights and over/unders). I won't speak more on this or throw stones, but I think the law of large numbers / averages means root sucks as precisely allocating weights, but generally better subnets do better, and worse ones do worse.

- Again, I have a bias in favour of this arguably, but I didn't realise this was rolling out beforehand. I actually think it's the right call to not announce it, as we would have seem massive sTAO weights / grift to lock in a starting position. The maths of the protocol actually means the hard selling from root will act as a natural stabiliser to some extent - starting at equal will actually materially disadvantage subnets that are "doing more" in the immediate sense, and damage production subnets. 

- The optimal GTO strategy if we go to 1/64 is to hot-reg as many subnets as possible in the next few days and just hard-sell the alpha - this is far worse for the protocol than giving a starting position to subnets that have worked for a long time.

My final point here. I think people talking about cabal vibes are being pretty rude here. @consτ [τ, τ] can be accused of many things, but I don't think this is really fair. 

I respect his decision either way on this, and think it's pretty crass to hammer this as grift / ruining the system, when it's clearly something that's been thought of in good conscience.

For example, I think it would be possible to create a smooth transition scheme from the old system to the new system by splitting the TAO emission per block into 2 parts. 50% (i.e. 0.5 TAO) created per block would be distributed to subnets through validator votes, as it was before, and 50% - using dTAO.

This way, we would be able to see the real decisions of stakers and how this affects the emission of subnets. At the same time, if stakers were not able to evaluate really good subnets - we would still have 50% of the weight from validators, as it was before. This would allow those subnets to continue to exist that are good, but for some reason the stakers did not appreciate them and do not want to invest TAO.

And only after some time, it would be possible to switch to dTAO by 100%.
